        'Incorrect. Ontario law does not prohibit engaging a non-OAA firm as a design architect — it prohibits a non-OAA licensed professional from sealing and stamping the permit drawings submitted to the municipality. The legal restriction is on the permit submission function, not on involvement in the design process. Foreign architects contribute to Ontario projects regularly through the design architect model.',
        'Correct. The OAA licence requirement is specifically about who can seal the permit drawings — the "architect of record." The building department requires a set of permit drawings sealed by an OAA-licensed professional. The standard solution on prestige projects is to engage the high-profile design firm for the creative design work and an experienced OAA-licensed Ontario firm as architect of record who carries the design through the technical, code compliance, and permit submission process. The design architect and architect of record roles are distinct: the former shapes the building; the latter bears professional responsibility for the permit set. This is a common and well-established arrangement in the GTA market.',
        'Incorrect. The OAA licence requirement applies to architectural drawings — the complete permit set — not only to structural drawings. A New York architect cannot seal the architectural permit drawings in Ontario regardless of whether an Ontario structural engineer is engaged. The distinction between architectural and structural drawings does not affect the licensing requirement for the architectural portion.'
